defaultDoes the UK have the skills base to remain a centre for the extractive industries and to ensure that UK based businesses benefit from potential future opportunities such defaultas shale gas?default&#xa0;
defaultIt is well known within the extractives sector that there is a national and global shortage of people with the skills required. This is also the case with other sectors requiring similar skill sets, such as advanced manufacturing. The UK is 
defaultnot producing enough people with technical skills and qualifications.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe UK extractives sector is a dynamic, technology-driven industry requiring Level 3 and higher level Science Technology Engineering and Maths (STEM) qualifications, particularly engine
defaulters and skilled technicians.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe UK Commission for Employment and Skills forecast a demand for around 1.9 million workers with engineering skills up to 2020, of which almost 90% are replacement jobs as the existing workforce retires. This equates to over 
default87,000 new workers each year qualified to Level 4+ and 69,000 qualified to Level 3.
default&#xa0;
default42% of employers requiring STEM skills have difficulties recruiting. The UK produces less than half number of required engineers at Level 4 and less than 40% at Level 3. A low participation rate in STEM subjects at Key Stage 4 is a key part of the problem.
default In 2009/10 just 16% of entrants achieved GCSEs at A*-C in 3 Sciences and Maths (vital for progression to A levels) and only 56% of schools entered pupils for ‘triple Science’ GCSEs.
default&#xa0;
defaultSirius Minerals recognises this issue and the challenge we face in reali
defaultsing our commitment to maximising local employment in the York Potash Project. The Company is continuing to invest in an education and skills programme that ensures the right skills are available in the local area. 
